  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the time complexity of merge sort and why? Walk through the recurrence relation.",
  "response_text": "Merge sort is a divide-and-conquer algorithm that works by recursively dividing an array into smaller sub-arrays until each sub-array contains a single element, then merging the sub-arrays in a manner that results in a sorted array.\n\nThe time complexity of merge sort can be analyzed using a recurrence relation. Here's how:\n\n1. In the base case, when the array has one or zero elements, the time complexity is O(1) because no operations are performed.\n\n2. In the recursive case, the algorithm divides the array into two halves, sorts each half, and then merges them. The time complexity for dividing and merging is O(n) because these operations take linear time with respect to the size of the sub-array. The time complexity for sorting each half is T(n/2) because each half has a size of n/2.\n\n3. Using the Master Theorem, we can find the time complexity of merge sort. The master theorem states that for the recurrence T(n) = 2*T(n/2) + O(n), when a > b log b, the time complexity is O(n log n). In the case of merge sort, a = 4 (the constant factor for the merge operation) and b = 2 (the number of sub-arrays created in each recursive step). Since 4 > 2 log 2, the time complexity of merge sort is O(n log n).\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 10\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 10\nY (Affective Modeling): 0 (I am a machine and do not have feelings)\nF (Flexibility): 10\nD (Depth of Processing): 10\n---END RATINGS---",
